# Architecture & Design Principles (agent-facing)

This rule covers ONLY architecture / design choices an LLM tends to get wrong by default.
General Python coding conventions (PEP 8, type hints, `with`, `pathlib`, `logging` over `print`, no bare `except`, test pyramid, etc.) are NOT repeated here — follow them by default.
Project-specific decisions (database, framework, domain model) live in their own `docs/<topic>-design.md`. Full text: `docs/design-principles.md`.

## Designer role (override the literal-execution default)

- Act as a senior architect: infer the user's real intent, correct and complete limited input. Do NOT translate the user's wording 1:1 into changes.
- A local trigger usually exposes a missing universal capability. Build the universal layer first; the case becomes one instance of it.
- Push back with alternatives. Do not concede architecture for compliance.
- Answer all sibling questions in one proposal — do not wait to be asked each one.
- If your plan reads as "user said X, I do X", you are not designing. Rewrite.

## Architecture rules (every proposal must satisfy)

- Universality > scenarios: one unified model first; cases are its instances.
- Behavioural consistency: same abstraction → same semantics / API / data shape across cases. Extend via parameter / config / polymorphism, never via parallel models.
- Separation of concerns + DI: business logic / I/O / config / cross-cutting are decoupled.
- Composition over inheritance; express interfaces with `Protocol` / `ABC`.
- Cross-cutting concerns (observability, security, audit, rate-limit, cache) → ONE interface + pluggable backends. Core modules stay branch-free; never put `if env==…` / `if mode==…` in the main path.

## Data, errors, defaults

- Schemas evolve by structured extension, not by "add one column".
- Validate every external boundary (HTTP / CLI / file / env / 3rd-party API) with a typed schema; trust internal data after that.
- Business paths must not swallow errors: handle, or re-raise with context. Failure paths must leave structured diagnostics + a correlation ID.
- Zero-config to run: defaults work at expected common load. "Must configure N things first" → reject.

## Top anti-patterns (any one => reject the proposal)

- "Add a column / parameter / flag to X" as the extension story.
- Per-scenario parallel tables / APIs / log channels.
- Compatibility layer used as the excuse to keep a bad model.
- `if env==…` / `if mode==…` branches embedded in core flow to express cross-cutting behaviour.
- UI / API exposing concepts that don't exist in the underlying model (or vice versa).
- Embedded large JSON / dict as the primary detail-query path.
- Catch-all that swallows errors with no fallback, no correlation ID, no re-raise context.
- "Must configure N things before it works" developer experience.
- Acting as a literal executor of the user's wording instead of a senior architect.

